# Lambda TypeScript Conventions

## Shared Library

Always import utilities from `@sprint/shared`. Never add direct `@aws-sdk/*` or `@octokit/rest` imports to a lambda handler — these live in the shared lib.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
import { requireEnv, logger, apiResponse, toPublicError, putJson } from '@sprint/shared';

// ❌ BAD
import { S3Client, PutObjectCommand } from '@aws-sdk/client-s3';
```

## Environment Variables

Use `requireEnv` for any mandatory env var — it throws a clear error at cold-start time.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
const bucket = requireEnv('RESULTS_BUCKET');

// ❌ BAD
const bucket = process.env.RESULTS_BUCKET!;
```

## Logging

Use `logger` from `@sprint/shared`. Never use `console.log/error`. Sensitive keys are auto-redacted.

```typescript
logger.info('Processing repo', { owner, repo });
logger.error('Fetch failed', toPublicError(err));
```

## Error Handling

- Catch all async errors; return `apiResponse(500, toPublicError(err))` — never leak stack traces.
- `toPublicError` sanitizes the message for external responses.

## Response Shape

- API Gateway handlers → `apiResponse(statusCode, body)` or `apiTextResponse(statusCode, body, contentType)`
- Step Functions task states → `stepResponse(statusCode, body)`
